      "content": "Inflation is like a sneaky goblin that slowly gnaws away at the value of your money over time. So, if you have $162,000 saved up in 30 years, it won't buy as much as $162,000 does today. To figure out how much that $162,000 would be worth in today's dollars, considering an average inflation rate of 3%, we can use the present value formula:\n\nPV = FV / (1 + inflation_rate)^number_of_years\n\nPlugging in the numbers:\n\nPresent Value (PV) = $162,000 / (1 + 0.03)^30\nPV ≈ $162,000 / (2.427262)\nPV ≈ $66,849.79\n\nSo, if inflation is a persistent goblin, the purchasing power of your savings would be equivalent to approximately $66,849.79 in today's money. This means that while you will have $162,000 saved in your account, you should expect goods and services to cost 30% more than they do today, if inflation stays at 3% annually. Always remember that actual inflation rates can vary from year to year, so the actual value in today's dollars could be slightly different.",
